Those two are Patecko's OC's. The one on the right he based on a Slavic myth of Lady Midday, a demon that would hunt men that would wander around fields at noon. He definitely seems to base her more off of the Polish side of Slavic mythology given not only the name "Poludnica" he gave her, without the "Å", but also the broken Polish he put in that pic, and the general imagery that's more akin to Polish traditional dresses. Wouldn't be surprised if his main inspiration is The Witcher which needless to say is heavily based on Polish Slavic mythology and history.

I believe Patecko is Serbian and the "dobar dan" is most likely another pointer to that. In Serbian, you have "Ð´oÐ±ap Ð´aÐ½", which is "dobar dan" transliterated. It means "good morning", but in Polish it would be "dzieÅ dobry".

Similarly, the whole sentence "oh ty kurwa jebina lisica! suka nenormalna!" seems like him trying to imitate Polish with his Serbian and a tinge of ESL showing up.

Not him, but ayylmaos with floof are an old sci-fi concept. The author Cordwainer Smith (real name Paul Linebarger, an Army psychological warfare specialist, which may or may not be meaningful), created a setting he called the Rediscovery of Mankind. It is in the very far future, in which humans learned to travel faster than light long ago, colonized other stars, forgot about the mother planet, then returned, to try to recreate old cultures and old ways to learn what they had forgotten. In them, Earth is governed by a ruthless and very competent dictatorship that calls itself the Instrumentality of Mankind (yes, like Evangelion. Hideaki Anno is a fan of old American sci-fi) even though the population of Earth is almost entirely uplifted animals. "The Ballad of Lost C'Mell" is a dark fairy tale about a beautiful cat-woman named C'mell, who falls in love with a human, the Lord Jestocost ("Cruelty" in Russian) as they plot to bring about political changes that grant rights and citizenship to the beast-derived "underpeople." (no points for guessing it was written in the 1960s).

There were others. Poul Anderson wrote stories in a far-future setting he called the Psychotechnic League, a loose alliance of human-settled worlds. There was a series of adventure stories with the human David Falkayn, and in one of them, The Trouble Twisters, he is partnered with an alien catgirl named Chee Lan. She is eerliy cute, hot-tempered, and foul-mouthed, and about three and a half feet tall. See image. It was also written in the 1960s.

There must be more but I can't think of them offhand.
